Url.Title: Selecting a Language
Url.Abstract: Selecting a Language Three languages are currently available for the TA Instruments Q Series related programs and instruments: English, German (Deutsch), Japanese () and Chinese (). Follow the instructions provided in the topics linked below to change to the desired language.

Url.Title: Using the TA Instrument Explorer
Url.Abstract: Using the TA Instrument Explorer The TA Instrument Explorer Window is a customizable graphical user interface for TA Messaging Agent (TAMA). It enables users to setup, view and control any instruments currently connected to the supplied private Ethernet Hub or a Local Area Network (LAN). The TA Instrument Explorer is also used to monitor the status of data transmission from the instrument to any controller via the Data File Acceptor (DFA).

Url.Title: Introducing the Q5000 IR and Q5000 SA
Url.Abstract: Introducing the Q5000 IR and Q5000 SA Two new instruments have been added to the TA Instruments Q Series®—the TGA Q5000 IR (Infrared) Thermogravimetric Analyzer (shown to the left) and the Q5000 SA Sorption Analyzer (shown to the right). Both instruments have an Autosampler, which allows you to load more than one sample and program the instrument for long term experiments.

Url.Title: Introducing the Touch Screen
Url.Abstract: Introducing the Touch Screen The Q5000 instruments have a built-in integrated display and keypad in the form of a touch screen for local operator control. The functions shown on the screen change depending upon the menu you are using. This section briefly describes the functions of the keys shown on the touch screen displays.

Url.Title: Introducing the Q5000 Autosampler
Url.Abstract: Introducing the Q5000 Autosampler The Q5000 Autosampler allows you to place multiple samples on the platform for automatic loading and run sequencing.

Url.Title: About the Humidity Chamber
Url.Abstract: About the Q5000 SA Humidity Chamber The Q5000 SA Humidity Chamber is used to run samples that will be exposed to a desired level of relative humidity.

Url.Title: About the Hi-Resolution TGA Option
Url.Abstract: TGA is particularly useful for observing the thermal decomposition of compounds. When individual thermal decompositions occur at well separated temperatures, quantitative information about sample composition can be obtained from the percent weight change at each transition. However, many TGA decomposition transitions overlap or appear drawn out in temperature due to the time-dependent nature of the reactions taking place. This overlap substantially reduces the ability to obtain an accurate measurement of weight change and reaction temperature.

Url.Title: About the Modulated TGA Option
Url.Abstract: About the Modulated TGA™ Option Q5000 IR Only Introduction TA Instruments Modulated TGA (MTGA™) is an innovative technique that is used with the Thermogravimetric Analyzer, TGA Q5000 IR. This option is used to study the same decomposition or volatilization properties as conventional TGA. However, MTGA provides unique capabilities that increase the amount of information obtained from a single TGA experiment, thereby improving the quality of interpretation.

Url.Abstract: Setting Up the System Configuration Choose from any of the four possible system configurations when setting up and installing the TA Instruments Advantage Q Series™ system. See the following descriptions for each type:

Url.Title: Licensing
Url.Abstract: Licensing Licensing is only required for Integrity™ and instrument options. Consult the instructions below for viewing, requesting, and installing controller and instrument licenses.

Url.Title: Connecting the Ethernet
Url.Abstract: Connecting the Ethernet In order to connect the instrument to a network, you will need to make the necessary cable connections as described below. The instrument and controller will be connected to a 12-port Ethernet switch. In addition, there are instructions for connecting the controller to a Corporate LAN.

Url.Title: Selecting Internet Protocol (IP) Addresses
Url.Abstract: Selecting Internet Protocol (IP) Addresses The Q Series™ instruments use the operating system VRTX. This operating system has certain restrictions on IP addressing and non-adherence to these restrictions will cause the instrument to be non-operational. If this should occur, the instrument’s IP address can be set back to the default IP address [172.23.160.31] by pressing [STOP] [STOP] [START] [STOP] on the instrument’s touch screen. Another limitation of the VRTX O/S is that the instruments are incapable of doing Classless Inter-Domain Routing, which results in the subnet being enforced by class. Listed below are the ranges of the IP addresses for each class as specified by the IANA.

Url.Title: Connecting Purge Gas Lines
Url.Abstract: Connecting Purge Gas Lines This topic provides information on connecting the lines as follows: Q5000 IR Sample and Balance Purge Gas Lines

Url.Title: Connecting a Spectrometer
Url.Abstract: Connecting a Spectrometer The Q5000 IR furnace allows you to connect a spectrometer, such as an FTIR or mass spectrometer to the instrument. This topic provides information needed to connect either type of spectrometer.

Url.Title: Installing and Maintaining the Heat Exchanger
Url.Abstract: Installing and Maintaining the Heat Exchanger The heat exchanger contains a liquid reservoir that supplies the instrument with coolant to dissipate heat from the furnace. The coolant exits the heat exchanger through the supply line, circulates to the furnace, and comes back to the reservoir via the return line.

Url.Title: Installing a Voltage Configuration Unit
Url.Abstract: Installing a Voltage Configuration Unit You may require the use of a voltage configuration unit if you use 230 Vac, rather than 120 Vac. Follow these steps to install the unit on the Power Control Unit (PCU):

Url.Title: Installing/Replacing the Hang-Down Wires
Url.Abstract: Installing/Replacing the Hang-Down Wires The Q5000 has two hang-down wires—one for the sample pan and one for the reference (tare) pan. A reference or tare pan is used to null the balance when no sample is present. The hang-down wires need to be replaced if they become damaged or bent. This document describes the procedures needed to either install (for the first time) or replace the wires. To align the balance after this procedure click here Aligning the TGA Balance.

Url.Title: Using the Instrument Setup Wizard
Url.Abstract: Using the Instrument Setup Wizard The Instrument Setup Wizard is used to synchronize the instruments and PC’s date and time, update module software, change the instrument's touch screen language, reset the instrument's parameters, and configure the instrument's network settings.

Url.Title: Selecting the Instrument Preferences
Url.Abstract: Selecting the Instrument Preferences You can set up certain operating parameters for your instrument through the instrument control software by selecting Tools/Instrument Preferences. Several pages will be displayed to allow you to set these parameters. To display the desired page of Instrument Preferences, click on the corresponding tab.

Url.Title: Q5000 IR Purge Gases and Flow Rates
Url.Abstract: Q5000 IR Purge Gases and Flow Rates The Q5000 IR instruments utilize purge gases during experiments. Choosing the TGA Q5000 IR Purge Gases

Url.Title: Selecting Signals to Store
Url.Abstract: Selecting Signals to Store Every analytical instrument produces distinctive signals that may or may not be stored in a data file. To select the signals that you want to be saved in data files produced during this experiment, access the Summary Page in Experimental View. This list will vary based on whether your options. Click the button. Check the signals to be stored from the list shown. Then click the OK button.

Url.Title: Using the Schedule Page
Url.Abstract: Using the Schedule Page (A Platinum Feature) Select the Platinum button at the bottom left-hand side of the main instrument control window.

Url.Title: Using the Messaging Page
Url.Abstract: Using the Messaging Page (A Platinum Feature) Email and Windows® Messaging are built-in Platinum features of the Advantage software for the Q5000. This feature provides a mechanism for the controller software to communicate with the operator based on subscribed events.

Url.Title: Using the File Utility
Url.Abstract: Using the File Utility Select Tools/File Utility menu item to open the File Utility window that allows you to view the contents of the following types of files:

Url.Title: Balance Conditioning
Url.Abstract: Balance Conditioning Balance conditioning is required for the Q5000 in order to achieve optimum performance from your instrument and keep your balance housing dry. Balance conditioning is needed when the instrument is first installed and whenever the balance housing is opened.

Url.Title: Calibrating the Touch Screen
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Touch Screen The instrument touch screen may need calibration from time to time to adjust the pressure spots on the screen for proper alignment. Follow these steps to calibrate the touch screen:

Url.Title: Calibrating the Q5000 - Overview
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Q5000 - Overview To ensure that your Q5000 is properly installed and providing accurate experimental results, you (or your TA Instruments service representative) should calibrate the instrument when you first install it, and then verify the results on suitable standard samples. To ensure that your results continue to be accurate over time, you should validate your instrument results periodically using certified (or well-characterized) samples.

Url.Title: Calibrating the Autosampler
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Autosampler This topic presents information for needed for maintaining proper Autosampler operation. Choose the desired link from the list below:

Url.Title: Calibrating the Punching Mechanism
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Punching Mechanism When using sealed aluminum pans, the punching operation is dependent on several calibration positions.

Url.Title: Calibrating the Q5000 IR Mass Flow Controllers
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Q5000 IR Mass Flow Controllers Under normal circumstances the mass flow controller (MFC) should not need to be calibrated by you, the customer. Calibration is done at TA Instruments for you. These calibration tables can be viewed by accessing Calibrate/MFC Sample 1, Calibrate/MFC Sample 2, or Calibrate/MFC Balance. If you need to return the calibration values to their factory settings for any reason, click the Restore Values button and the original calibration values will be restored.

Url.Title: Calibrating the Q5000 SA Mass Flow Controllers
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Q5000 SA Mass Flow Controllers The Q5000 SA mass flow controllers (MFCs) are precise devices that are factory calibrated and verified using a rigorous procedure. The resultant calibration tables can be viewed by accessing Calibrate/MFC Dry or Calibrate/MFC Humidified. If you need to return the calibration values to their factory settings for any reason, click the Restore Values button and the original calibration values will be restored.

Url.Title: Calibrating the TGA Q5000 IR Temperature
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the TGA Q5000 IR Temperature Temperature calibration is useful for experiments in which precise transition temperatures are essential. To temperature calibrate the TGA, you need to analyze a high-purity magnetic standard for its curie temperature, and then enter the observed and correct values in the temperature calibration table.

Url.Title: Calibrating the TGA Q5000 SA Temperature
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the TGA Q5000 SA Temperature The temperature calibration for the Sorption Analyzer is a six-point calibration that is performed and verified by the factory during the manufacturing process. At installation your service representative verifies the factory calibration. This calibration measures the difference in temperature of the thermistor against a certified NIST calibrated thermometer. If the thermistor should need to be recalibrated for any reason, contact TA Instruments Service to schedule that calibration.

Url.Title: Verifying the Q5000 SA Humidity
Url.Abstract: Verifying the Q5000 SA Humidity The Q5000 SA uses an "open loop" arrangement for generating and measuring the humidity level in the chamber around the same and reference. The humidity is generated by controlling the ratio of gas passing through two calibrated Mass Flow Controllers (MFCs). These Mass Flow Controllers are calibrated at the factory prior to shipment using a certified external flow measurement device. Proper calibration is verified at installation (and can be periodically verified by the operator) by running deliquescent salts. TA Service uses sodium bromide, which deliquesces at 57.6 + 2 %RH (absolute) at 25°C for verification.

Url.Title: Analyzing TGA Calibration Data
Url.Abstract: Analyzing TGA Calibration Data Performing calibration, verification, or validation on your instrument requires experimental data. Follow the procedures in this topic to gather and analyze that data.

Url.Title: Setting Up Calibration Standards
Url.Abstract: Setting Up Calibration Standards This function is used to define the default settings for each calibration standard, add new standards, and/or reset the existing standards.

Url.Title: Calibrating the Weight
Url.Abstract: Calibrating the Weight Weight calibration is required when you first install the Q5000 IR or Q5000 SA systems. After initial calibration, weight verification should be performed periodically (once a month is recommended) and, if necessary, recalibration should be performed.

Url.Title: Calibration Report
Url.Abstract: Calibration Report If an instrument has been properly calibrated, a calibration report can be generated. Select Calibrate/Report from the main menu to display a window such as the one shown to the right.

Url.Abstract: To open the Instrument Control Window for each of the Q Series™ Instruments, go to the TA Instruments Explorer and double click on the instrument icon to connect to the selected instrument and automatically open the Instrument Control Window.

If you choose to use the touch screen, you can access either the Status or Display options. See also:Display Menu Touch Screen.

The red check mark indicates that the method segment has been successfully completed and the green arrow signifies the current running method segment.

Url.Title: Basic Steps Needed to Run a Q5000 Experiment
Url.Abstract: Basic Steps Needed to Run a Q5000 Experiment All of your Q5000 experiments will have the following general outline. In some cases not all of these steps will be performed.

Url.Title: Preparing Samples
Url.Abstract: Preparing Samples Preparing Solid Samples The TGA has high sensitivity to weight changes. Therefore, there is no advantage to using large samples. 10 to 50 milligram samples are recommended. However, when evaluating solids or powders, make sure that the sample is prepared and introduced into the pan so that it evenly covers the bottom of the pan. This is important because surface area (and the associated interaction with the purge gas) can affect results.

Url.Title: Choosing a Pan
Url.Abstract: Choosing a Pan The Q5000 instruments have the following pans available. Choose a pan based on the desired temperature range and application. The pan size and material are specified through the instrument control program on the Summary Page. Proper selection is important to ensure optimum performance is achieved and pan punching is initiated (only when a sealed pan is selected).

Url.Title: Preparing Sealed TGA Pans
Url.Abstract: Preparing Sealed TGA Pans Sealed aluminum pans are available for use with the Q5000 IR and Q5000 SA. They are used with the punching mechanism for opening sealed pans before the experiment. The ability to encapsulate samples prior to placing them in the Autosampler tray and to open them just before loading into the furnace serves to prevent loss of volatiles to the environment or to avoid adsorption of moisture by a hygroscopic material while the material is awaiting analysis.

Url.Title: Taring the Pan(s)
Url.Abstract: Taring the Pan(s) The Tare function ensures that the weight measured by the balance reflects the weight of the sample only.

Url.Title: Preweighing Your Samples
Url.Abstract: Preweighing Your Samples When conducting experiments on the TGA you may wish to weigh the samples before the experiment begins in order to find out how much weight is lost by the samples while they are sitting on the sample tray waiting for the run to begin. To do this follow the steps below (it will take approximately two minutes to preweigh each pan):

Url.Title: Loading/Unloading a Sample
Url.Abstract: Loading/Unloading a Sample Samples should only be loaded into clean, tared pans to ensure proper weight measurement. The amount of sample to load is dependent on numerous factors: sample form, density, amount of weight loss/gain expected, and pan capacity. In general, for an unknown sample, start with a sample size of approximately 20 mg.

Url.Title: Adjusting the Event, Storage, Gas, and Air Cool Selections
Url.Abstract: During an active experiment the data storage, event, gas, and air cool states are controlled by the method parameters and/or method segments. However, you may manually change the state of these selections using the Control menu.

Url.Title: Specifying a Test Procedure
Url.Abstract: Specifying a Test Procedure When running experiments on your instruments you will need to specify a test procedure. A procedure contains all of the information regarding a test protocol (see below). The sample and calibration information are not part of a procedure.

Url.Title: Creating Custom Methods
Url.Abstract: Creating Custom Methods You have two options when creating procedures. You can choose to use one of the available pre-preprogrammed templates or you can choose a custom test and create your own method. A custom method can contain up to 225 segments. This help topic describes how to create a custom method.

Url.Title: Starting a Run and/or Sequence
Url.Abstract: Starting a Run and/or Sequence If more than one run is contained in the run sequence, the scheduled run (run with the arrow pointing to it) will be executed. To schedule a run, prior to starting the experiment, move the pointer (cursor) along the left of the run numbers, you should see the pointer change to an arrow. When it becomes an arrow, you can then click the mouse to position the arrow next to the selected run number. This run becomes the scheduled run, which is the experiment that will be run when Start is selected.

Url.Title: Holding/Resuming an Experiment
Url.Abstract: Holding/Resuming an Experiment When an experiment is in progress you can temporarily suspend it and continue it later by using the following operations:

Url.Title: Modifying a Running Method

Url.Title: Stopping/Rejecting an Experiment
Url.Abstract: Stopping/Rejecting an Experiment When an experiment is in progress you can stop it and save the data or reject it and discard the data as directed below:

Url.Title: Data File Transfer
Url.Abstract: The Data Transfer function allows data to be manually transferred from the instrument to a specified location and file. The instrument can only store data from one experiment at a time; therefore, to save the data it must be transferred from the instrument prior to the start of the next run. The data is normally transferred automatically from the instrument to the controller; however, if the Data File Acceptor (DFA) fails to transfer the data file successfully at the end of the run, the software will automatically post an error message indicating that the file was not received from the instrument.

Url.Title: Available Q5000 Test Templates
Url.Abstract: Available Q5000 Test Templates You can either select one of the preprogrammed test templates list below or select "Custom" to create your own procedure using the Method Editor. The list of test templates is based on frequently used experimental methods.

Url.Title: Segment List
Url.Abstract: Segment List A segment is a preprogrammed series of instructions used in a method. Several segments can be linked together to create the desired method. The available segment list will vary depending on the instrument and optional accessories installed.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Procedure Page
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Procedure Page The Procedure Page is used to specify the test conditions and to save the custom test to a procedure file, if desired.

Url.Title: Saving, Restoring, and Viewing Procedures
Url.Abstract: Saving, Restoring, and Viewing Procedures When running experiments on your instrument, you will be either creating a new custom procedure files, selecting a preprogrammed procedure, or restoring a saved procedure file. A procedure contains all of the information regarding the test protocol (mode, signals, method segment, advanced parameters, and post-test options).

Url.Title: File Naming
Url.Abstract: File Naming NTFS file systems can support filenames up to 255 characters. Since MS-DOS cannot recognize long filenames, Windows NT server automatically translates long names of files and folders to 8-character filenames with 3-character extensions for MS-DOS users.

Url.Title: Choosing Real Time Signals to Plot
Url.Abstract: Choosing Real Time Signals to Plot To edit the Real Time Plot signals, select Tools/Real Time Plot Signals from the main menu or position your cursor in the RealTime Plot pane, right click the mouse and select Signals from the pop-up menu. The window displayed allows you to choose which signals to plot, the line type (for Y1 and Y2 axes) and grid type, and the color and scaling desired for each signal selected.

Url.Title: Choosing the Advanced Parameters
Url.Abstract: Choosing the Advanced Parameters Use the Advanced Parameters window to define more advanced instrument parameters that may not normally be changed for experiments, once they are set.

Url.Title: Entering Post Test Options
Url.Abstract: Entering Post Test Options Select the Procedure Page, then click the Post Test button to access the Post Test Parameters window, which is used to define functions that will occur at the end of a run.

Url.Title: Selecting Post Test Actions
Url.Abstract: Selecting Post Test Actions While an experiment is in progress you can change the process that occurs after the end of a test run.

Url.Title: Using the Summary Page
Url.Abstract: Using the Summary Page Sample information for each run is entered on both the Summary Page and Notes Page. The Procedure Page is used to set up the experimental test conditions.

Url.Title: Setting Up the Notes Page
Url.Abstract: Setting Up the Notes Page Sample information for each run is entered on both the Summary Page and Notes Page. The Procedure Page is used to set up the experimental test conditions.

Url.Title: Handling Run Sequences
Url.Abstract: Handling Run Sequences When running experiments on your instrument, you will be either creating new run sequences using custom or preprogrammed procedures or restoring a saved run sequence.

Url.Title: Conventional TGA Experiments
Url.Abstract: Conventional TGA Experiments You have chosen to perform a conventional TGA experiment. Now you need to select which type of conventional TGA experiment to perform from those listed on the window.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Curie Point Temperature Calibration
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Curie Point Temperature Calibration (Q5000 IR Only) Temperature calibration is useful for TGA experiments in which precise transition temperatures are essential. There are two techniques for TGA temperature calibration recognized by the American Society for Testing and Materials. These techniques are described in ASTM Standards E914-83 and E1582-93. The latter, which is based on the Curie Point of paramagnetic metals, is recommended for the TA Instruments TGA's.

Url.Title: Setting Up a TGA Heat and Hold Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a TGA Heat and Hold Procedure Heat and Hold experiments are used to assess the thermal stability of materials over time at elevated temperatures. They are also used to assess the rate of volatiles (water, solvent) evolution/drying at a specific temperature, as well as the adsorption/desorption of gases in applications such as catalyst reactivity, porosity of ceramics and oxidative stability.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Hi-Res TGA Dynamic Rate Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Hi-Res™ TGA Dynamic Rate Procedure It has long been known that using very slow heating rates will improve the separation of some overlapping transitions and, thus, increase the resolution of the TGA scan. This is the situation when using the Dynamic Rate experiments.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Hi-Res TGA Constant Reaction Rate Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Hi-Res™ TGA Constant Reaction Rate Procedure In constant reaction rate, the heating rate is varied as required to maintain a constant pre-selected rate of weight change (%/minute). Whenever the rate of weight change exceeds the percent/minute threshold, the heating rate of the furnace is reduced, even to the point of cooling if necessary. When percent/minute falls below the threshold, the heating rate is increased up to the maximum specified for the ramp segment. Weight change resolution is improved because sample heating is reduced or reversed during weight changes allowing them to complete at the selected reaction rate before moving on to the next weight change.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Modulated TGA Standard Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Modulated TGA Standard Procedure Conventional TGA can be used to study the kinetics of volatilization or decomposition processes using a number of experimental approaches including the multiple heating rate approach specified in ASTM (American Society for Testing & Materials) Method E 1641. Modulated TGA allows similar kinetic information to be obtained from a single experiment by applying a modulated heating profile to the material, which in effect is comparable to applying multiple constant heating rates simultaneously. Hence, Modulated TGA saves time.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Modulated TGA with Hi-Res Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Modulated TGA with Hi-Res™ Procedure You have chosen to perform a Modulated TGA (MTGA) experiment. Now you need to select which type of Modulated TGA experiment to perform from those listed on the window.

Url.Title: Setting Up a TGA Ramp with Gas Switch Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a TGA Ramp with Gas Switch Procedure Most TGA experiments are performed by heating the material at a constant rate from ambient temperature to a temperature above the point of total decomposition. The purge gas that surrounds the material is switched at an elevated temperature in a Ramp with Gas Switch procedure to cause additional weight changes to occur. A variety of inert and “reactive” purge gases can be used, including nitrogen, argon, helium (inert) and air, oxygen (reactive). Gas switching experiments generally involve switching from an inert to reactive gas at a specific temperature. For example, carbon black determinations are achieved by switching from nitrogen to oxygen at 600°C.

Url.Title: Setting Up a TGA Ramp Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a TGA Ramp Procedure Most TGA experiments are performed by heating the material at a constant rate from ambient temperature to a temperature above the point of total decomposition. The purge gas that surrounds the material remains the same throughout the experiment. A variety of inert and “reactive” purge gases can be used, including nitrogen, argon, helium (inert) and air, oxygen (reactive).

Url.Title: Setting Up a TGA Stepwise Isothermal Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a TGA Stepwise Isothermal Procedure A technique to increase resolution is raising furnace temperature until the onset of decomposition and then holding temperature isothermally until the decomposition is complete. After which, the temperature is raised again until the next decomposition begins, and so on until the final temperature of interest is reached.

Url.Title: Humidity Experiments
Url.Abstract: Humidity Experiments (Q5000 SA Only) Templates are available to help guide a new Q5000 SA user in setting up common humidity experiments. Those templates (shown below) can also be accessed through the Wizard to further simplify the process.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Humidity Ramp Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Humidity Ramp Procedure This experiment measures the amount of water adsorbed by a sample as the relative humidity is ramped (increased or decreased) at a constant rate at a constant temperature.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Sorption Isotherm
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Sorption Isotherm This experiment increases or decreases the relative humidity in a stepped fashion while holding the temperature constant.

Url.Title: Setting Up an Isohume Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up an Isohume Procedure This experiment maintains the relative humidity at a constant level while holding the temperature constant.

Url.Title: Setting Up an Adsorption Desorption Procedure
Url.Abstract: Setting Up an Adsorption/Desorption Procedure This experiment measures the amount of water adsorbed and desorbed over a range of relative humidity at a constant temperature.

Url.Title: Setting Up a Salt Deliquescence Experiment
Url.Abstract: Setting Up a Salt Deliquescence Experiment When you perform a Salt Deliquescence experiment on the Q5000 SA, the following test parameters need to be specified:

Url.Title: Starting the Experimental Wizard
Url.Abstract: Starting the Experimental Wizard TA Instruments offers several basic types of experiments, depending upon the instrument, as seen on the Experimental Wizard opening window.

Url.Title: Entering Sample Information Using the Wizard
Url.Abstract: Entering Sample Information Using the Wizard Use this dialog to enter or select additional information to be stored with the selected file. These items cannot be changed once the experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: Entering Notes and Gas Settings Using the Wizard
Url.Abstract: Entering Notes and Gas Settings Using the Wizard Use this dialog to enter or select additional information to be stored with the selected file. These items cannot be changed once the experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: Scaling Axis Window
Url.Abstract: Scaling Axis Window Set up the lower and upper axis limits for the RealTime plot display area. You can choose to have the limits set automatically, using the data as it is collected, or you can choose to manually enter the axis limits desired. See the description of each type below.

Url.Title: Viewing a Procedure Summary
Url.Abstract: Viewing a Procedure Summary This is a view-only window that displays the contents of the current procedure file. This window contains the following information:

Url.Title: Viewing the Q5000 Information
Url.Abstract: Viewing the Q5000 Information Select View/TGA Information from the menu to open a window displaying the following selected information about your instrument. Choose the applicable instrument below.

Url.Title: Selecting User Preferences
Url.Abstract: Selecting User Program Preferences The User Preferences window provides default programming options that you can use to customize your Instrument Control program.

Url.Title: Aligning the Balance
Url.Abstract: Aligning the Balance (Q5000 IR and Q5000 SA) To avoid weight signal noise, the instrument must be level so that the sample pan and hang-down wire hang inside the furnace without touching the sides. The angle at which the pan hangs is very sensitive to slight irregularities in bench top surfaces, so it is recommended (required for Q5000 IR instruments) that you use a marble table for your instrument.

Url.Title: Cleaning the Instrument
Url.Abstract: Cleaning the Instrument Different techniques must be used when cleaning various parts of the Q5000 instruments. Choose from the list below for detailed information.

Url.Title: Eliminating Static
Url.Abstract: Eliminating Static Some materials readily build up static electricity changes that can create problems during loading. The Q5000 IR is designed with a unique hang-down wire assembly that provides a direct path to ground when metal pans are used. Hence, no static effects will be seen with those pans.

Url.Title: Cleaning the Sample Pans
Url.Abstract: Cleaning the Sample Pans NOTE: The aluminum pans are not meant to be cleaned or reused. They are disposable pans.

Url.Title: Configuring the Instrument Log
Url.Abstract: Configuring the Instrument Log To sort the instrument messages for display in the instrument log, check those that will be displayed and leave those that you do not wish to be displayed blank. You can choose to sort the messages by the categories displayed or by the severity of the message.

Url.Title: Installing the Humidity Close-Out Disks
Url.Abstract: Installing the Humidity Close-Out Disks The Q5000 SA humidity close-out disks prevent condensation from forming on the top surface of the sample chamber when an experiment is in progress. When you first receive your instrument those disks are not yet installed. Follow these instructions to install the disks:

Url.Title: Replacing Fuses
Url.Abstract: Replacing Fuses WARNING: Always unplug the instrument before you examine or replace the fuses. Replacing the Q5000 Fuses

Url.Title: Replacing the Q5000 SA Humidity Sensor
Url.Abstract: Replacing the Q5000 SA Humidity Sensor The relative humidity (RH) is controlled by a pair of very precise Mass Flow Controllers (MFCs). Sensors located near the sample and reference provide ongoing verification that the relative humidity achieved is what was requested. Failure of one or both of these sensors does not jeopardize the performance of the instrument.

Url.Title: Replacing the Q5000 IR Lower Furnace Assembly
Url.Abstract: Replacing the Q5000 IR Lower Furnace Assembly Weight changes in TGA are typically plotted versus sample temperature as measured by a thermocouple located close to the sample inside the lower furnace assembly. This lower furnace assembly is exposed to sample off-gases and to contamination if the sample sputters or foams during decomposition. The lower furnace assembly will need to be replaced, if it becomes contaminated and cannot be cleaned. Embrittlement due to long term cycling up to 1200°C will also require replacement.

Url.Title: Replacing the Q5000 IR Bulbs
Url.Abstract: Replacing the Q5000 IR Bulbs If you start to experience problems holding the desired temperature for your experiments, you may need to replace the halogen bulbs used in the Infrared furnace. Use the Platinum Auto Diagnostics functions to test for IR bulb failure.

Url.Title: Q5000 Autosampler Cycle Test
Url.Abstract: Q5000 Autosampler Cycle Test The Q5000 Autosampler Cycle Test functions are used to test the Autosampler pan loading, unloading, punching, and furnace functionality. To perform an Autosampler Cycle test, touch the CALIBRATION key on the touch screen then touch the Autosampler button on the Calibration screen. Select the Cycle Test tab, the touch screen shown in the figure below is displayed. This screen is provided to cycle the autosampler through its actions to test each function. A brief description of the function of each item is provided in the table below.

Url.Title: Q5000 Autosampler Motor Test
Url.Abstract: Q5000 Autosampler Motor Test The individual motors of the instrument can be executed using the Autosampler Motor test functions. To perform an Autosampler Motor test, touch the CALIBRATION key on the touch screen then touch the Autosampler button on the Calibration screen. Select the Motor tab, the touch screen shown in the figure below is displayed. Press the button to move the desired motor.

Url.Title: Transporting the Q5000 IR
Url.Abstract: Transporting the Q5000 IR Important: If you need to ship this instrument, you will need to contact TA Instruments' Service to properly package the instrument for shipment. Improper packaging will result in damage to the instrument.

Url.Title: Transporting the Q5000 SA
Url.Abstract: Transporting the Q5000 SA Important: If you need to ship this instrument, you will need to contact TA Instruments' Service to properly package the instrument for shipment. Improper packaging will result in damage to the instrument.

Url.Title: Updating Software and Downloading a Language
Url.Abstract: Updating Software and Downloading a Language Before you can use the instrument you must install the instrument software. This process is done initially when the instrument is shipped and periodically thereafter as new updates are released. You can also load a new language file during this process.

Url.Title: Using the Instrument Log
Url.Abstract: Using the Instrument Log The Instrument Log displays the current list of instrument messages along with the log time (date and time), run, category, and a brief description of what occurred. The entries displayed in this log include: instrument errors, run status (e.g., starting stopping, and rejecting runs), calibration (when new calibration results are saved), data file acceptor (path and filename of stored data), Autosampler (loading and unloading of pans), miscellaneous and power supply messages, taring (which TGA pan(s) are tared and its offset).

Url.Title: Clearing the Instrument Log
Url.Abstract: Clearing the Instrument Log You can selectively clear off the instrument messages, if desired, using this window. You can select the Keep the Last button then choose the Month(s) and Week(s) that you wish to leave in the log.

Url.Title: Q5000 Replacement Parts
Url.Abstract: Q5000 Replacement Parts Replacement parts for the Q5000 that you can replace yourself are available from TA Instruments. See the table below when ordering parts. To locate the closest representative, click here TA Instruments Offices. Click on one of the following categories to jump to the list of parts in that grouping:

Url.Title: DFA Troubleshooting Guide
Url.Abstract: DFA Troubleshooting Guide When troubleshooting Data File Access (DFA) errors, the root cause almost always falls into one of the following three categories; improperly configured User-accounts, improper Share Permissions, and/or improper NTFS Security settings. The following steps listed below pertain only to DFA errors generated when saving data files to the local machine.

Url.Title: Using the Punch Force Test
Url.Abstract: Using the Punch Force Test NOTE: This option is available in Service mode only. Contact TA Instrument service, if you require assistance with the pan punching mechanism.

Url.Title: Analysis Limits Error
Url.Abstract: Analysis Limits Error Analysis limits must be between ___ and ___. You have exceeded the analysis limits required for this experiment. Please reselect the limits and try again.

Url.Title: Analysis Limits Range
Url.Abstract: Analysis Limits Range The analysis limits must be between ____ and ____. You have exceed the analysis limits range. Please correct the limits chosen and try the operation again.

Url.Title: Apply Setup Changes
Url.Abstract: Apply Setup Changes You have made some change on your setup pages. You need either Apply or Cancel the changes before you can implement other operations.

Url.Title: Bad Instrument Type
Url.Abstract: Bad Instrument Type The instrument type selected for this operation is inappropriate. Select a different instrument type and try again.

Url.Title: Balance Abnormal
Url.Abstract: Balance Abnormal The balance is in ___ state. Make sure you have put correct weight on the sample pan. Do you really want to continue the next step?

Url.Title: Baseline Sample Size is Nonzero
Url.Abstract: Baseline Sample Size is Nonzero Warning: Baseline sample size is non-zero. The calibration may not be accurate.

Url.Title: Calibration Data Not Accepted
Url.Abstract: Calibration Data Not Accepted The instrument did not accept the calibration data. Retry the calibration.

Url.Title: Calibration File Generated by Wrong Instrument
Url.Abstract: Calibration File Generated by Wrong Instrument Not a < > calibration file. The calibration file you have selected is not valid for the current instrument, it was created for a different instrument. Select a calibration file that applies to the current instrument or create a new file.

Url.Title: Calibration Not Complete. Exit Anyway?
Url.Abstract: Calibration Not Complete. Exit Anyway? At least one of the calibration files has not been analyzed or saved. Do you still want to leave this calibration view?

Url.Title: Calibration Signals Not Found
Url.Abstract: Calibration Signals Not Found Not a valid < > calibration file. Missing signals. The data file that you have selected to analyze for calibration purposes does not contain the signals specific for calibration purposes (for example, you may have a file that was not created in the proper mode) or you have not selected the correct signals to store in the calibration mode. Therefore, you will not be able to use this file for calibration purposes. Use a calibration file that contains all of the information needed.

Url.Title: Cannot Change Calibration Settings
Url.Abstract: Cannot Change Calibration Settings Calibration parameters can not be changed while an experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: Cannot Change Calibration Settings
Url.Abstract: Cannot Change Calibration Settings Calibration parameters can not be changed while an experiment is in progress.

Url.Title: Cannot Connect to Instrument
Url.Abstract: Cannot Connect to Instrument The destination computer can not connect to the instrument. Please check the connection between that computer and the instrument and then try again.

Url.Title: Cannot Detect MAC Address
Url.Abstract: Cannot Detect MAC Address The controller program can not determine the instrument's MAC address. You may need to reboot the Windows and try to connect again.

Url.Title: Cannot Enter Zero Value
Url.Abstract: Cannot Enter Zero Value Must enter a value other than zero. This message appears if you either leave a required field blank or enter a zero value in that field. You must enter a value other than zero in this field in order to proceed. See the online help for further information.

Url.Title: Cannot Open Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Cannot Open Calibration File The calibration file you have selected cannot be opened. The file may be faulty or it may be of the wrong type. Try opening a different calibration file.

Url.Title: Cell Has Been Removed
Url.Abstract: Cell Has Been Removed The cell has been removed. This message lets you know that the cell has been removed from the instrument. In order to operate again another cell must be installed.

Url.Title: Cell Has Been Replaced
Url.Abstract: Cell Has Been Replaced The cell has been replaced. This message lets you know that a different cell has been installed on the instrument.

Url.Title: Change X Axis?
Url.Abstract: Change X Axis? The curve contains analysis results which will be deleted when this change is made. Do you want to continue to change the x-axis?

Url.Title: Close Advantage?
Url.Abstract: Close Advantage Q Series? You have chosen to close this program. If there are any experiments in progress when the program is closed, any data collection to the controller will not be lost.

Url.Title: Close Application
Url.Abstract: Close Application Since a new program was downloaded to the instrument, this application will now close.

Url.Title: Confirm Change
Url.Abstract: Confirm Change You must either confirm the change or click Cancel before you can switch to the next page.

Url.Title: Confirm Lid Closure
Url.Abstract: Confirm Lid Closure The instrument is currently running. Are you sure you want to close the lids? The instrument is currently performing an operation and you have selected to close the AutoLid.

Url.Title: Confirm Lid Open
Url.Abstract: Confirm Lid Open The instrument is currently running. Are you sure you want to open the lids? The instrument is currently performing an operation and you have selected to open the AutoLid.

Url.Title: Correction Greater Than 50°C
Url.Abstract: Correction Greater Than 50°C You have tried to save a temperature calibration in which the difference between the observed and the correct temperatures for one temperature calibration point is greater than 50°C. This is not allowed.

Url.Title: Data File Saved
Url.Abstract: Data File Saved The data file will be saved to the destination. If there is a file with the same name, it will be appended a time stamp in its name. Do you want to continue?

Url.Title: Data Not Continuous
Url.Abstract: Data Not Continuous The data is not continuous between the selected limits. The data in the selected file used for calibration analysis is not continuous between the two limits that you have selected.

Url.Title: Data Not Continuous Between Limits
Url.Abstract: Data Not Continuous Between Limits The data in the selected file used for calibration analysis is not continuous between the two limits that you have selected.

Url.Title: Data Transfer
Url.Abstract: Data Transfer This message is displayed when data is transferred from the instrument to the controller.

Url.Title: Delete Calibration Files?
Url.Abstract: Delete Calibration Files? At least one of the calibration files has not been analyzed or saved. Do you still want to remove files from the list?

Url.Title: Difference Greater Than 50 Degrees
Url.Abstract: Difference Greater Than 50 Degrees Difference Between Observed and Corrected is greater that 50°C. Calibration is not acceptable.

Url.Title: Direct Command Control Error
Url.Abstract: Direct Command Control Error Load Direct Command Control's DLL error! Code %d This is an internal error that is caused because the DCC.dll file was not found.

Url.Title: Do You Want to Clear Log?
Url.Abstract: Do You Want to Clear Log? Are you sure you wish to clear the log? This message is displayed after you click the Clear Log button on the Instrument Log. It just confirms that you wish to delete all of the entries from the log stored by the instrument.

Url.Title: Do You Want to Exit?
Url.Abstract: Do You Want to Exit? The experiment is currently running. Closing this application will not stop data collection. However it will stop the data replication to the archive directory. You may need to copy the data file to the archive directory later.

Url.Title: Download Complete. Reset Instrument
Url.Abstract: Download Complete. Reset Instrument Software download successfully completed. Press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: Download Successful
Url.Abstract: Download Successful Software download successfully completed. Press the OK button to close this program and restart the instrument.

Url.Title: Dual Sample Not Applicable
Url.Abstract: Dual Sample Not Applicable Invalid file. Dual sample file selected for single sample instrument. You have attempted to use a dual-sample file for a single-sample instrument. Make sure that you use a file obtained from a single-sample DSC for this operation.

Url.Title: Enter Acceptable Value
Url.Abstract: Enter Acceptable Value Enter a value between XX and XX. Enter the values for the entry field again. The value you have already entered is not within the range shown.

Url.Title: Error Reading From File
Url.Abstract: Error Reading From File

Url.Title: Error Reading Tzero Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Error Reading Tzero Calibration File There is a problem with the Tzero calibration file you have attempted to use. Check the filename and try again. If the error persists, you may need to generate a new file.

Url.Title: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked
Url.Abstract: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked < > not found. Software compatibility between controller and instrument is not checked.

Url.Title: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked
Url.Abstract: Error Software Compatibility Not Checked < > not found. Software compatibility between controller and instrument is not checked.

Url.Title: Error Writing to File
Url.Abstract: Error Writing to File

Url.Title: Exotherm Values Different
Url.Abstract: Exotherm Values Different The Exotherm values of the two files are different. The two files selected calibration analysis do not have matching exotherm properties. These files cannot be used together for the calibration. Choose two files with similar exotherm properties for calibration purposes.

Url.Title: Exotherm Values of the Two Files are Different
Url.Abstract: Exotherm Values of the Two Files are Different The two files selected calibration analysis do not have matching exotherm properties. These files cannot be used together for the calibration. Choose two files with similar exotherm properties for calibration purposes.

Url.Title: Extrapolated Point Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Extrapolated Point Out of Range Extrapolated point is out of range.

Url.Title: Failed to Create Object
Url.Abstract: Failed to Create Object Unable to create object. Make sure the object is entered in the system registry.

Url.Title: Failed to Open File for Writing
Url.Abstract: Failed to Open File for Writing

Url.Title: Failure. Retry Operation
Url.Abstract: Failure. Retry Operation Verify transferred string file failed. You need to retry again. This message is displayed during the downloading of instrument software using the Tools/Instrument Setup wizard. The file transfer (download) was not successful. Do not reset the instrument.

Url.Title: File Already in Use
Url.Abstract: File Already in Use The file you have attempted to load is already being used elsewhere and cannot be accessed. Choose another file.

Url.Title: File Backup Done
Url.Abstract: File Backup Done The Backup operation has been completed. This is a confirmation message to let you know that the instrument file backup operation has been successfully completed.

Url.Title: File is for Different Cell
Url.Abstract: File is for Different Cell The cell serial number of the calibration file you have selected does not match the cell installed on the instrument. Choose the appropriate matching calibration file or repeat the experiment.

Url.Title: File is Not Available
Url.Abstract: File is Not Available The file ___ is not available for download. Use the TA Instruments Advantage CD and completely reload the software. If the error persists, contact TA Instruments for assistance.

Url.Title: File Needs Sample and Reference Sizes
Url.Abstract: File Needs Sample and Reference Sizes The file selected for calibration has zero sample and reference sizes. Sample sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: File Not Analyzed. Remove From List?
Url.Abstract: File Not Analyzed. Remove From List? During the calibration process at least one of the calibration files has not been analyzed or saved. This message is displayed to make sure that you still want to delete the file. Click Yes to delete or No to cancel this operation.

Url.Title: File Not Available
Url.Abstract: File Not Available File was not available for download. The file that you have attempted to use cannot be located in the directory specified. Please check the filename and location to make sure the file is present as specified and try the operation again. If this message persists, you will need to use or create a different file for download.

Url.Title: File Not Found
Url.Abstract: File Not Found The file named in the command does not exist in the current directory or search path specified, or the filename was entered incorrectly.

Url.Title: File Not Found
Url.Abstract: File Not Found Instrument Control was unable to find the file requested. This may occur if the file was moved to a different location on the computer or if the file was renamed.

Url.Title: Force File Not Found
Url.Abstract: Force File Not Found File "Force.xls" not found on Instrument.

Url.Title: Furnace Close at Method End
Url.Abstract: Furnace Close at Method End This message confirms that the furnace will close at the end of the sequence.

Url.Title: Heat Flow Results Not Optimized
Url.Abstract: Heat Flow Results Not Optimized Heat flow results using this pan type are not optimized. See online help for further details. Are you sure you want to make this change?

Url.Title: Inappropriate Files. Transfer Anyway?
Url.Abstract: Inappropriate Files. Transfer Anyway? The files in currently selected directory are not for the instrument. Do you still want to transfer them to the instrument?

Url.Title: Incompatible Software Version
Url.Abstract: Incompatible Software Versions The current version of instrument software is not compatible with the controller. Please go to the Instrument Setup Wizard and download the latest version of instrument software before proceeding.

Url.Title: Incorrect Instrument Type
Url.Abstract: Incorrect Instrument Type Incorrect instrument type chosen in SelectCalType(). The instrument that you have chosen is not compatible with the operation selected. Please choose another instrument.

Url.Title: Incorrect Method for Instrument
Url.Abstract: Incorrect Method for Instrument The method file selected is not applicable to the instrument (and cell type) installed or the filename may be incorrect. The method file is for a different instrument family. For example, a TGA method file was read by a DSC.

Url.Title: Instrument Control Message Open File Failure
Url.Abstract: Open File Failure The file you have specified is inaccessible. It may be already in use, or the file format may not be recognized by the program.

Url.Title: Instrument Currently Receiving Files
Url.Abstract: Instrument Currently Receiving Files The instrument is receiving files. If you cancel this operation, the instrument will not reboot and run correctly. You must resend the files to instrument BEFORE YOU CAN REBOOT it. Are you sure you want to continue?

Url.Title: Instrument Did Not Accept Calibration
Url.Abstract: Instrument Did Not Accept Calibration The instrument did not accept the calibration data. Retry the calibration.

Url.Title: Instrument Type Not Supported
Url.Abstract: Instrument Type Not Supported The instrument type is not supported or the required component is missing for the instrument!

Url.Title: Insufficient Instrument Disk Space
Url.Abstract: Insufficient Instrument Disk Space The instrument does not have enough free flash disk space to download a new executable file. Call TA Service.

Url.Title: Internal Message
Url.Abstract: Internal Message This is a message that is internal to the program. If this message persists, contact TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Invalid Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Invalid Calibration File The calibration file you have selected is not recognized as a TA Instruments calibration file. Select another file or create a new one.

Url.Title: Language Cannot Load - English is Default
Url.Abstract: Language Cannot Load - English is Default The Language initialization has failed - unable to read registry, defaulting to English.

Url.Title: Language Does Not Reside in Instrument
Url.Abstract: Language Does Not Reside in Instrument The selected language does not exist in the instrument. You must update module software.

Url.Title: Language Initialization Failed
Url.Abstract: Language Initialization Failed Language initialization failed. Check to see if TAIE_(JPN, DEU, or CHS).dll is present.

Url.Title: Language Selection Successful
Url.Abstract: Language Selection Successful Change of language successfully completed. Press the OK button to close this program and then press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: Less Than Two Points
Url.Abstract: Less Than Two Points Less than 2 points in calibration. The calibration file selected does not have enough points to allow successful calibration. Either select another calibration file with more than two points or create a new calibration file.

Url.Title: Load Macro File
Url.Abstract: Load Macro File The file is not a valid TA Instruments macro file. This can occur if the file was created using a different application and has the extension .mac.

Url.Title: Local Communication Queue is Overflowing
Url.Abstract: Local Communication Queue is Overflowing There is no more space in the communication queue. Wait until the system completes the tasks currently in progress, then repeat the operation. This message is caused by slow communication rate between the controller and instrument. If the error persists, call TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Master Function Only
Url.Abstract: Master Function Only A non-master user is not allowed to set DCC (ID %d) to the instrument. In order to perform this function you need to register as the master controller for that particular instrument. If someone else is already logged in as the master, that person must unregister before you can log in again as the master controller.

Url.Title: Method Segment Has Invalid Temperature Limits
Url.Abstract: Method Segment Has Invalid Temperature Limits To correct the problem, edit the invalid temperature value in the method file. See the online help reference to determine the temperature limit applicable to the instrument. Then run the edited procedure.

Url.Title: Method Segment Has Invalid Type
Url.Abstract: Method Segment Has Invalid Type To correct the problem, edit the invalid segment in the method file. See the online help reference to determine the temperature limit applicable to the instrument. Then run the edited procedure.

Url.Title: Must Log In as Master Controller
Url.Abstract: Must Log In as Master Controller This program requires you log in as a master controller. However, One of the controllers on the network is connected as a master already. You need unregister the master on that controller and try to log in again.

Url.Title: Must Recalibrate When Heat Flow Changed
Url.Abstract: Must Recalibrate When Heat Flow Changed Changes to this heat flow selection require that you recalibrate cell constant and temperature. Are you sure you want to make this change?

Url.Title: No Calibration Weight
Url.Abstract: No Calibration Weight No calibration weight sizes specified. While performing an SDT Weight Calibration, the second file (with weights) used for this calibration does not have any calibration weight sizes specified and therefore cannot be used.

Url.Title: No Changes Allowed
Url.Abstract: No Changes Allowed You are not allowed to make any change on the current run. The instrument is running a method. You cannot make changes to the method in progress. You must wait until the method is complete or stop the method in progress.

Url.Title: No Module Information
Url.Abstract: No Module Information Calibration file contains no module info. The data file that you have selected to analyze for calibration purposes does not contain information specific to the type of instrument that generated the file. You will not be able to use it for calibration purposes. Use a calibration file that contains all of the information needed.

Url.Title: No More Method Segments
Url.Abstract: No More Method Segments You have reached the maximum number of segments (255) allowed in a method. To add another segment you must first delete a segment to make room.

Url.Title: No Sample and Reference Sizes
Url.Abstract: No Sample and Reference Sizes The file selected for calibration has zero sample and reference sizes. Sample sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: No TGA Calibration Weight Sizes Specified
Url.Abstract: No TGA Calibration Weight Sizes Specified While performing a TGA Weight Calibration on the SDT instrument, the second file (with weights) specified for this calibration does not have any calibration weight sizes specified and therefore cannot be used.

Url.Title: Not a Tzero Calibration File
Url.Abstract: Not a Tzero Calibration File The file you have attempted to load is not a valid Tzero calibration file. If was not obtained using the correct method as generated through the calibration wizard.

Url.Title: Not a Valid Macro File
Url.Abstract: Not a Valid Macro File ____ is not a valid autoanalysis macro file. The file selected is not a valid TA Instruments Autoanalysis macro file, which needs to be created using the Universal Analysis program. Select a valid file before proceeding.

Url.Title: Not All Data in Range is On
Url.Abstract: Not All Data in Range is On If you turn the data collection off and then back on during a calibration experiment, you can get some gaps in your data file. The resulting file has some “off” regions in it. When you analyze that data for calibration purposes, and the “off” regions are within the analysis range, you will get this error message.

Url.Title: Not All Data is On
Url.Abstract: Not All Data is On Not all data in range is ON. Some of the data found in the calibration data file was not turned on. This data will not be used in the calibration analysis.

Url.Title: Not TA Method
Url.Abstract: Not TA Method The method file that you have selected to open is not a valid TA Instruments method file.

Url.Title: Number of Cycle Markers Incorrect
Url.Abstract: Number of Cycle Markers Incorrect There are an incorrect number of cycle markers in this method for a Tzero calibration. The Tzero calibration is based on two experiments (baseline and sapphire), which are conducted using a very specific method. The expected method was not found (e.g., the number of cycle markers not as expected). Check the method log for these files and conduct one or both of these experiments again using the calibration wizard only. Do not modify the running method during these tests.

Url.Title: OLE Failed
Url.Abstract: OLE Failed Ole register drop target failed. This error is displayed when the segment list is not working properly. Close the Thermal Advantage Q Series™ program and restart it.

Url.Title: OLE Initialization Failed
Url.Abstract: OLE Initialization Failed OLE initialization has failed. Make sure that the OLE libraries are the correct version.

Url.Title: Operation Failed. Do Not Reset. Try Again.
Url.Abstract: Operation Failed. Do Not Reset. Try Again. Verify transferred program file failed. You shall not reset your instrument. Please try to send files again.

Url.Title: Operation Illegal for Non-Master
Url.Abstract: Operation Illegal for Non-Master This operation is illegal for a non-master controller. In order to make changes to the experiment you must be registered as the master controller of this instrument. If you are not the master controller you may simply view the progress of the experiment.

Url.Title: Operation is Prohibited
Url.Abstract: Operation is Prohibited This operation is prohibited by the 21 CFR restriction. You cannot perform this operation as set forth by the 21 CFR 11 guidelines.

Url.Title: Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Out of Range Enter a number between XX and XX. Enter the values for the entry field again. The value you enter must be within the range shown.

Url.Title: Password Incorrect. Try Again
Url.Abstract: Password Incorrect. Try Again The password is incorrect! You have to try again. The password as entered is incorrect. Please check the spelling and try again.

Url.Title: Peak Onset Error
Url.Abstract: Peak Onset Error When you selected the data limits for analysis, the marker was not placed within the limits of an existing peak integration.

Url.Title: Please Reset Instrument
Url.Abstract: Please Reset Instrument Please press the reset button on the back of the instrument to complete the process.

Url.Title: Press to exit dialog and accept data
Url.Abstract: Press to exit dialog and accept data When you click the OK button, you accept the items chosen or entered on the window and the window closes.

Url.Title: Press to exit dialog with no changes
Url.Abstract: Press to exit dialog with no changes When you click the Cancel button, the calibration is aborted and the window is closed with no changes.

Url.Title: Press to learn about the dialog
Url.Abstract: Press to learn about the dialog Click the Help button to open the online help for this window.

Url.Title: Quench Cooler for Heat Flow T1 Only
Url.Abstract: Quench Cooler for Heat Flow T1 Only Quench Cooler can be used to determine Heat Flow T1 only. This message is displayed if you have selected Quench Cooler as your cooler type and either Heat Flow T4P or Heat Flow T4 as your heat flow selection on the Instrument Preferences/DSC Page. The Quench Cooler can only be used with Heat Flow T1.

Url.Title: Rename String File Failed
Url.Abstract: Rename String File Failed Rename string file failed. Do you still want to transfer the program file? This message is displayed when using the Tools/Instrument Setup wizard. Click the Next button until the Transfer Program Files to the Instrument window is displayed. When you update the module software you are actually sending two files to the instrument. The first file contains all the text the instrument needs. The second is the executable code. When you see the error message above, the transfer of the text file has failed. The string file and program files are matched sets. You cannot update just one.

Url.Title: Reset Time Over Temperature?
Url.Abstract: Reset Time Over Temperature? Do you wish to reset the time over 1400°C to zero? The instrument saves the number of minutes over 1400°C. When a new furnace is installed, this number is reset by the service technician to zero (0).

Url.Title: Restore Operation Successful
Url.Abstract: Restore Operation Successful The Restore operation has been completed. This is a confirmation message to let you know that the files have been successfully restored to the instrument.

Url.Title: Sample and Reference Sizes Not Required
Url.Abstract: Sample and Reference Sizes Not Required The file selected for calibration has sample and reference sizes specified. Zero sizes are expected for this calibration file.

Url.Title: Sample File Not Specified
Url.Abstract: Sample File Not Specified A valid filename for the sample data file must be entered into the Tzero filename dialog in order to perform a DSC Tzero calibration. Either create a sample file or locate one. Specify the new file and retry the operation.

Url.Title: Sample Interval Must be Divisible by 0.5
Url.Abstract: Sample Interval Must be Divisible by 0.5 The sample interval must be divisible by 0.5. When you enter the data sample interval, you must enter a number that is divisible by 0.5.

Url.Title: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than 0.0
Url.Abstract: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than 0.0 The file selected for calibration has a sample size of zero. A zero sample size is not valid for this calibration.

Url.Title: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than Zero
Url.Abstract: Sample Size Must Be Greater Than Zero The file selected for calibration has a sample size of zero. A zero sample size is not valid for this calibration.

Url.Title: Sample Size Too Small
Url.Abstract: Sample Size Too Small The file selected for calibration has a sample size of 0 (zero). A zero sample size is not valid for this calibration.

Url.Title: Sapphire Delta T Signal is Not Correct
Url.Abstract: Sapphire Delta T Signal is Not Correct The Sapphire Delta T signal is not lower than the Baseline Delta T signal value.

Url.Title: Save Calibration?
Url.Abstract: Save Calibration?

Url.Title: SDT Heat Flow Calibration - Sapphire Delta T Incorrect
Url.Abstract: SDT Heat Flow Calibration - Sapphire Delta T Incorrect The sapphire delta T signal value is not lower than the baseline delta T signal value; therefore, the SDT heat flow calibration analysis cannot be performed.

Url.Title: Select Backup Directory
Url.Abstract: Select Backup Directory Select a Base Backup Directory to Save Instrument Files. Choose a backup directory that will be used to store instrument files.

Url.Title: Select Cycle Test
Url.Abstract: Select Cycle Test Please select the test type. This message is used for Service only. It prompts you to select the type of cycle test desired. Click OK and then select the desired cycle test type.

Url.Title: Select Restore Directory
Url.Abstract: Select Restore Directory This message is displayed when you are performing a service/restore option and you have not specified a directory. The directory specified should match the MAC address of the instrument.

Url.Title: Serial Number Incorrect
Url.Abstract: Serial Number Incorrect The calibration analysis results could not be saved because the number of the cell currently installed on the DSC does not match the cell number in the calibration data file used for analysis.

Url.Title: Service Menu Selected
Url.Abstract: Service Menu Selected You have just activated the Service menu. You must restart the application for the changes to take effect. This menu item will be removed after 8 hours or if the application is closed. Do you want to proceed?

Url.Title: Slow Communication
Url.Abstract: Slow Communication Either the instrument is too busy, locked-up, or the communication device is too slow.

Url.Title: Start and Stop Cannot Be The Same
Url.Abstract: Start and Stop Cannot Be the Same Start and Stop Points are the same. The specified start and stop points chosen for your analysis limits are the same point.

Url.Title: Too Hot for Pan
Url.Abstract: Too Hot for Pan The upper temperature limit for ____ pans is ___°C. Change either the pan type or the experiment temperature range.

Url.Title: Touch Screen Calibration Successful
Url.Abstract: Touch Screen Calibration Successful Instrument touch screen is successfully calibrated. This message is displayed after you have successfully calibrated the instrument touch screen. Click OK to exit.

Url.Title: Transfer Failed
Url.Abstract: Transfer Failed Transferred file failed. You should not reset your instrument. Please try to transfer files again.

Url.Title: Transfer Warning
Url.Abstract: Transfer Warning The file you are sending to the instrument is a critical file. If the transfer fails, the instrument may not run. Please use the Instrument Setup Wizard to transfer the file. Are you sure you want to continue?

Url.Title: Two Unique Filenames Must be Specified
Url.Abstract: Two Unique Filenames Must be Specified When you calibrate the SDT for DSC heat flow or TGA weight calibration, the two files specified cannot be the same.

Url.Title: Unknown Instrument Calibration
Url.Abstract: Unknown Instrument Calibration The instrument file that you have attempted to use for calibration purposes cannot be identified by the program. Use a file that is appropriate for the instrument being calibrated or create a new calibration file.

Url.Title: Unsupported Calibration Type
Url.Abstract: Unsupported Calibration Type There is a problem with the program. Please close all windows, exit the program, and restart the program again. If this problem is not resolved, call TA Instruments for service.

Url.Title: Verify Shutdown
Url.Abstract: Verify Shutdown Are you sure you want to activate an instrument shutdown? All communication to the instrument will be halted. Select YES to begin this process or NO to cancel operation. Once it is safe to turn off the instrument a message will be posted.

Url.Title: Weight Calibration Coefficients Incorrect
Url.Abstract: Weight Calibration Coefficients Incorrect While performing a TGA Weight Calibration on the SDT instrument, the calculated weight coefficients are outside the allowable limits. This calibration cannot be conducted using the specified data files.

Url.Title: Weight Calibration Out of Range
Url.Abstract: Weight Calibration Out of Range Weight calibration coefficients out of range. You have attempted to enter a weight value, during TGA Weight Calibration, that is either less than 10.0 or greater than 200.00 grams.

Url.Title: Window Already Open on Touch Screen
Url.Abstract: Window Already Open on Touch Screen Platform calibration window already opened on instrument touch screen.

Url.Title: Windows Sockets Initialization Failed
Url.Abstract: Windows Sockets Initialization Failed Contact TA Instruments Service for assistance.

Url.Title: Wrong Cell Number
Url.Abstract: Wrong Cell Number The calibration analysis results could not be saved because the number of the cell currently installed on the DSC does not match the cell number in the calibration data file used for analysis.

Url.Title: Wrong Cell Type
Url.Abstract: Wrong Cell Type Calibration file is for a different type of cell. The file you have attempted to load does not match the cell type installed on the instrument. Either choose a file that matches the cell type or conduct the experiment again.

Url.Title: Wrong File for Instrument
Url.Abstract: Wrong File for Instrument The file < > is not for the current instrument type. Do you want to continue?

Url.Title: Wrong Instrument Format
Url.Abstract: Wrong Instrument Format Cannot use the calibration file. It was written by a ___ not a ___. The calibration file selected is not applicable to the instrument (and cell type) installed or the filename may be incorrect. The calibration file is for a different instrument family. For example, a DSC calibration file was attempted for analysis by the TGA calibration function.

Url.Title: Instrument Control Advantage Integrity Help Topics
Url.Abstract: Instrument Control Advantage Integrity Help Topics Within the Advantage Integrity system, much of the operation of the Instrument Control program is unchanged when compared to its non–Integrity (standard) counterpart. Records are generated and saved to the database using the instrument control functions. You can view the records stored in the database from instrument control using View/Database Viewer, but the records can only be accessed through the Universal Analysis program.

Url.Title: Using an Integrity-Licensed Instrument Control
Url.Abstract: Using an Integrity-Licensed Instrument Control Once an instrument has been set up with an Advantage Integrity license, it will become part of the Advantage Integrity system. Access will be controlled, data will be stored in the Oracle database, and an audit trail will record events. Once you are logged in to the instrument, the basic operation of an Integrity instrument is the same as its non-Integrity (standard) counterpart for calibrating, setting up experiments, and starting runs.

Url.Title: Accessing the Integrity System
Url.Abstract: Accessing the Integrity System The Advantage Integrity Instrument Control and Universal Analysis programs are part of the closed system for creation and storage of electronic records. As such, each person must log in for identification and permission to use the system.

Url.Title: First Time Login
Url.Abstract: First Time Login When you open any software component of the Advantage Integrity system, either the TA System Manager Program, an Instrument Control program, or the Universal Analysis program, the Log in window is displayed.

Url.Title: Changing Your Password
Url.Abstract: Changing Your Password The Advantage Integrity system relies on password protection to maintain the integrity of the system and the audit trail. Your log in password may be changed at any time desired and must be changed when it expires. The expiration date is set by your TA Instruments System Manager. A few days before your password expires, you will begin to receive “password expiration” notices each time you log in. To change your password, follow these instructions:

Url.Title: Saving Records to the Database
Url.Abstract: Saving Records to the Database Data files produced from experiments are automatically saved to the secure database.

Url.Title: Sorting the Data in Tree View
Url.Abstract: Sorting the Data in Tree View You can change the way the database information is arranged, or sorted, in the left-hand pane's tree view by clicking the button on the Audit Trail Viewer or Database Viewer tool bar. This opens the Set Data Sort Order In Tree View window shown here.

Url.Title: Accessing Records in the Database
Url.Abstract: Accessing Records in the Database After logging into the Advantage Integrity-licensed Universal Analysis program, you may need to locate the experiment data in the database for analysis.

Url.Title: Extracting Records from the Database
Url.Abstract: Extracting Records from the Database Occasionally it may be necessary to extract a record from the database to generate a special report or send to TA Instruments for trouble-shooting purposes. When this occurs, the original record remains in the database and cannot be deleted or altered. To extract a record perform the following:

Url.Title: Viewing the Audit Trail
Url.Abstract: Viewing the Audit Trail The TA Instruments’ Integrity system provides secure, computer-generated, time-stamped audit trails to independently record events. Each record identifies the person, time/date, and a description of the event. Comments may be added, if desired, by the user.

Url.Title: Adding Comments to the Audit Trail
Url.Abstract: Adding Comments to the Audit Trail You can add a comment to an existing audit trail entry or add a new audit trail entry to further explain an action or event.

Url.Title: Audit Trail Transfer Status
Url.Abstract: Audit Trail Transfer Status When you log in or log out of an Integrity system the Audit Trail Transfer Status window may be displayed as messages are transferred from the instrument to the database.

Url.Title: Color Palette Window
Url.Abstract: Color Palette Window Use this window to choose a background color from the displayed colors.

Url.Title: Event Logging for TAMA
Url.Abstract: Event Logging for Q Series TAMA If after consulting the DFA Troubleshooting Guide, your instrument continues to generate DFA errors, enable Event Logging for Q Series™ TAMA using the instructions below. When the next DFA error occurs, email the following log files (Instrument Log, System Event Log and the Application Event Log) to TA Service.

Url.Title: Heater PID Method Segment
Url.Abstract: Heater PID Method Segment The Heater PID method segment is used to change the performance of the instrument furnace during the execution of a thermal method. PID stands for Proportional, Integral, and Derivative, the three modes of traditional temperature control. The Heater PID segment specifies the control coefficients for each mode of temperature control.

Url.Title: Experimental Checklist
Url.Abstract: Experimental Checklist Additional comments on proper experimental setup. Purge Gas: The Q5000 instruments are operated with two purge gas flows. In both models one purge gas flows through the balance housing. In the Q5000 IR the second purge gas flows through the furnace/sample area. In the Q5000 SA the second purge gas flows through the humidity chamber.
